 analyzing sites devoted to resource extraction explores how these places promote settler colonial understandings of land use. By contrast, Indigenous museums and cultural centres defy colonial messages in displays that adapt and refuse conventional museum formats.Honouring local, rural, and Indigenous knowledge, Voluntary Detours enriches critical accounts of the past, present, and future of museums.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHeritage tourismzAlberta. 0aHistoric siteszAlberta. 0aMuseum exhibitszAlberta. 0aMuseums and communityzAlberta. 0aSmall museumszAlberta. 7aART / Museum Studies.2bisacsh  aBlackfoot Crossing Historical Park.  aBrooks Aqueduct.  aCanadian.  aFear Wonder.  aFort Chipewyan Bicentennial.  aGopher Hole.  aIndigenous.  aOil Sands Discovery.  aWadey Centre.  aautomobility.  aclassification.  acolonialism.  adioramas.  aembodied experience.  agrass-roots.  ahauntology.  aheritage.  ahistoric.  amicromuseums.  amuseum studies.  anatural.  anostalgia.  aopen texts.  apetrocultures.  apioneer.  aplay.  arepresentations childhood.  aresource extraction sites.  arurality.  asettler colonial.  asmall.  ataxidermy.  atheories place.  atheory.  avisitors.  awestern Canada.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228009962?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228009962423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228009962/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles